02:16.737 --> 02:18.372
‐ Hmm.
‐ Of course.

02:18.405 --> 02:20.707
Have a good weekend.

02:20.741 --> 02:22.342
‐ This was in our inbox.

02:22.376 --> 02:25.245
Uh, it's for Jones, Baxter,
and Gray Partners.

02:25.278 --> 02:26.546
I don't even think
they're in this building.

02:26.580 --> 02:28.548
‐ [laughs]
I'm sorry.

02:28.582 --> 02:31.118
Um, the mailroom might be
a little too happy it's Friday.

02:31.151 --> 02:32.452
‐ [chuckles]
Maybe so.

02:32.486 --> 02:33.720
[inhales]

02:33.754 --> 02:35.088
‐ Thank you for
bringing it down,

02:35.122 --> 02:39.760
but, if there's a next time,
please let me send someone up.

02:39.793 --> 02:42.429
Your secretary should not
have been bothered with this,

02:42.462 --> 02:43.430
let alone you.
‐ [exhales softly]

02:43.463 --> 02:46.333
It was no problem.
I was heading out anyway.

02:46.366 --> 02:48.602
Have a good night.

02:48.635 --> 02:50.404
[laughs softly]
Linda.

02:50.437 --> 02:52.272
‐ Linda.
[chuckles]

02:52.305 --> 02:55.342
‐ See you.
‐ Okay.

02:55.375 --> 02:57.411
‐ These you always
put through.

02:57.444 --> 02:59.446
These, you put on hold
and ask him about.

02:59.479 --> 03:00.747
‐ Mm‐hmm.
‐ And all these here

03:00.781 --> 03:02.082
just say
you'll have him return.

03:02.115 --> 03:03.717
‐ Okay.

03:03.750 --> 03:06.119
‐ Are we gonna survive the week
without you, Colleen?

03:06.153 --> 03:07.254
‐ Daniel Broderick's office.

03:07.287 --> 03:09.589
‐ I'm gonna steal her,
show her our filing system.

03:09.623 --> 03:11.324
‐ Yes, they are.
When?

03:11.358 --> 03:13.760
‐ If you do have any questions
while she's gone,

03:13.794 --> 03:16.163
please don't hesitate.
I'd rather be interrupted

03:16.196 --> 03:17.531
than have something slip
through the cracks.

03:17.564 --> 03:19.132
‐ I will, thanks.

03:19.166 --> 03:21.735
Can I just say
how nice it is in here?

03:21.768 --> 03:25.205
Colors, the furnishings‐‐
so elegant, but welcoming.

03:25.238 --> 03:26.506
I don't know if you used
a decorator,

03:26.540 --> 03:27.774
but whoever did it,
I love it.

03:27.808 --> 03:28.775
[phone rings]

03:28.809 --> 03:31.278
‐ That's lovely of you to say.

03:31.311 --> 03:34.381
[pensive music]

03:34.414 --> 03:41.321
♪ ♪

03:45.892 --> 03:48.562
[exhales]
So what do we think?

03:48.595 --> 03:50.230
‐ Hi.
[laughs softly]

03:50.263 --> 03:52.566
It's amazing.

03:52.599 --> 03:56.303
It's an amazing office
that I can't believe is mine.

03:56.336 --> 03:58.505
Are you sure about this?
‐ Of course I'm sure‐‐

03:58.538 --> 04:00.507
‐ Because I think Colleen
might think it's crazy.

04:00.540 --> 04:03.210
‐ What's crazy?
‐ Me...

04:03.243 --> 04:05.512
as a paralegal.

04:05.545 --> 04:08.882
Me going from receptionist
to paralegal.

04:08.915 --> 04:12.385
‐ What, is this about
the typing?

04:12.419 --> 04:14.521
[laughs]

04:14.554 --> 04:16.056
Colleen's not
thinking anything.

04:16.089 --> 04:18.225
And even if she was,

04:18.258 --> 04:20.160
most things about
being a paralegal

04:20.193 --> 04:21.762
you can't really
be prepared for.

04:21.795 --> 04:23.730
You sorta gotta
learn on the job.

04:23.764 --> 04:27.534
But I promise, if you're not
perfect at it right away,

04:27.567 --> 04:29.336
I'll give you at least
50 more chances.

04:29.369 --> 04:31.905
Hmm?
[laughs]

04:33.373 --> 04:35.909
Hey, um, do you wanna
come observe me

04:35.942 --> 04:38.178
do the interview
with the Lindseys?

04:38.211 --> 04:41.848
Or would you rather stay
in here and worry some more?

04:41.882 --> 04:45.619
‐ Uh, observe and take notes.
[laughs]

04:45.652 --> 04:48.455
[Quarterflash's
"Take Me to Heart" playing]

04:48.488 --> 04:55.562
♪ ♪

04:55.595 --> 04:58.899
‐ ♪ You won't forget my eyes ♪

04:58.932 --> 05:03.270
♪ Ooh, deep inside
you realize ♪

05:03.303 --> 05:07.374
♪ You're gonna see me
wherever you go ♪

05:07.407 --> 05:12.979
♪ You're gonna hear me
on your radio ♪

05:13.013 --> 05:17.384
♪ There you are in your car ♪

05:17.417 --> 05:20.253
♪ And suddenly
you hear me ♪

05:20.287 --> 05:24.758
♪ "Do you want me,
do you want me" ♪

05:24.791 --> 05:26.626
♪ Take me to heart ♪

05:26.660 --> 05:28.895
♪ I promise you a miracle ♪

05:28.929 --> 05:30.730
♪ Take me to heart ♪

05:30.764 --> 05:33.333
♪ You're gonna be mine ♪

05:33.366 --> 05:34.901
♪ Take me to heart ♪

05:34.935 --> 05:39.573
♪ You know it's just
a matter of time ♪

05:39.606 --> 05:41.174
♪ ♪

05:41.208 --> 05:42.943
‐ First, they forgot
to check the monitor,

05:42.976 --> 05:47.614
then they misread it.
It was just an avalanche

05:47.647 --> 05:50.150
of underreaction
and negligence.

05:50.183 --> 05:52.986
‐ Did the baby die?
‐ Catastrophic brain damage.

05:53.019 --> 05:55.589
So, no, baby didn't die,
but her parents' hopes

05:55.622 --> 05:57.657
and dreams for her did.

05:57.691 --> 05:59.359
[sighs]
A good obstetrician would have

05:59.392 --> 06:02.495
seen the signs even if the
labor and delivery team didn't.

06:02.529 --> 06:05.098
But from what I understand,
it was just a matter of time

06:05.131 --> 06:08.468
before this guy destroyed some
family with his incompetence.

06:08.501 --> 06:11.771
‐ So what are you gonna do?

06:11.805 --> 06:13.840
‐ Gonna make him pay.

06:13.874 --> 06:16.076
[both laugh softly]

06:18.011 --> 06:21.948
Mm, apropos of nothing,
the, um, Collins report.

06:21.982 --> 06:25.452
‐ Tomorrow morning.
‐ Oh.

06:25.485 --> 06:29.422
If I haven't said it recently,
you're doing great.

06:29.456 --> 06:32.459
‐ I'm glad.
[laughs]

06:32.492 --> 06:36.396
Because‐‐just‐‐

06:36.429 --> 06:38.531
You make me wanna do great.

06:38.565 --> 06:40.867
‐ [laughs softly]

06:40.901 --> 06:44.738
[pensive music]

06:44.771 --> 06:47.707
[indistinct chatter
and laughter]

06:47.741 --> 06:49.342
‐ She's just putting
sand on it.

06:49.376 --> 06:51.912
‐ [laughs]
‐ Okay, I'll race you.

06:51.945 --> 06:58.885
♪ ♪

07:12.799 --> 07:14.968
‐ How was your weekend?

07:15.001 --> 07:16.937
‐ Huh.

07:16.970 --> 07:19.372
Long.

07:19.406 --> 07:21.374
Would you help me with the
Staedtler deposition at 10:00?

07:21.408 --> 07:23.076
‐ I‐‐of course.

07:23.109 --> 07:25.345
‐ Thank you.

07:25.378 --> 07:28.448
‐ Law offices
of Dan Broderick...

07:28.481 --> 07:31.718
Just a moment.
Linda...

07:31.751 --> 07:33.820
Phone for you.
‐ Oh, okay.

07:35.922 --> 07:37.590
[phone ringing]

07:37.624 --> 07:40.060
Hello, this is Linda.

07:40.961 --> 07:42.295
Hello?

07:42.329 --> 07:44.397
[line clicks]

07:44.431 --> 07:46.900
Hello?

07:46.933 --> 07:49.769
[ominous music]

07:49.803 --> 07:53.073
♪ ♪

07:53.106 --> 07:55.809
‐ I said, get rid of her.

07:55.842 --> 07:58.645
‐ You thought it was
your decision.

07:58.678 --> 08:00.513
You think you decide
who works for me...

08:00.547 --> 08:02.716
[scoffs]

08:02.749 --> 08:06.586
For my practice, where I
make the money that you spend.

08:06.619 --> 08:07.454
You don't.

08:07.487 --> 08:10.557
I pay for your life,
everything about it.

08:10.590 --> 08:12.826
I pay for this house
that you live it in.

08:12.859 --> 08:17.430
So if anyone's gonna be
getting out, it's you.

08:20.867 --> 08:23.737
‐ Are you sleeping with her?
‐ [sighs]

08:27.040 --> 08:29.743
[scoffs]
Why would you even ask me that?

08:29.776 --> 08:31.745
‐ Are you?

08:31.778 --> 08:32.879
‐ If this is where
your head goes

08:32.912 --> 08:36.916
when you don't get your way,
that's the real problem.

08:36.950 --> 08:39.119
You should get some
professional help for that.

08:39.152 --> 08:41.921
‐ A lawyer would say you still
haven't answered the question.

08:41.955 --> 08:44.624
‐ I am not sleeping
with Linda Kolkena.

08:44.657 --> 08:47.927
I haven't and I'm not.

08:50.530 --> 08:52.699
‐ In a marriage,
under that marital contract,

08:52.732 --> 08:54.167
people rely on each other.

08:54.200 --> 08:56.036
They feel safe
with one another.

08:56.069 --> 08:59.839
But that safety
carries a price.

08:59.873 --> 09:03.410
When you have complete faith,

09:03.443 --> 09:06.746
vulnerability means what occurs

09:06.780 --> 09:09.649
with the loss of that faith‐‐

09:09.682 --> 09:14.921
the separation from any sense
of the realities of one's life.

09:14.954 --> 09:17.957
[keys clacking]

09:17.991 --> 09:20.860
[light dramatic music]

09:20.894 --> 09:25.865
♪ ♪

09:25.899 --> 09:28.101
‐ [laughs softly]

09:28.134 --> 09:29.536
[chuckles]

09:29.569 --> 09:33.039
[breathes deeply]

09:33.073 --> 09:35.975
[sighs deeply]

09:36.009 --> 09:38.678
Hi.
I thought you left.

09:38.711 --> 09:41.181
‐ [pants lightly]

09:41.214 --> 09:43.316
‐ Is everything all right?
Are you‐‐

09:43.349 --> 09:46.553
‐ [sighs]
Can you come here please?

09:49.556 --> 09:52.859
‐ What's wrong?
What can I do?

10:01.835 --> 10:02.836
[Quarterflash's
"Take Me to Heart" playing]

10:02.869 --> 10:04.537
‐ ♪ Want me ♪

10:04.571 --> 10:06.506
♪ Do you want me ♪

10:06.539 --> 10:08.608
♪ Do you want me ♪

10:08.641 --> 10:11.544
♪ Do you want me ♪

10:11.578 --> 10:13.279
♪ Take me to heart ♪

10:13.313 --> 10:15.548
♪ Don't deny the miracle ♪

10:15.582 --> 10:17.517
♪ Take me to heart ♪

10:17.550 --> 10:21.054
♪ Surrender's
just a motion away ♪

10:21.688 --> 10:24.691
♪ It's just
a motion away ♪

10:25.091 --> 10:28.128
[upbeat music]

10:28.161 --> 10:34.834
♪ ♪

10:38.438 --> 10:39.706
‐ She was a total mega bitch
last night,

10:39.706 --> 10:42.108
even worse than usual.

10:42.142 --> 10:44.777
I mean, telling Karen it was
her fault for abandoning Chip?

10:44.811 --> 10:46.045
‐ And what about Abby?
‐ [scoffs]

10:46.079 --> 10:47.046
‐ I mean, she's just gonna
let Diana stay with them

10:47.080 --> 10:49.949
and not even ask her about
Chip being a murderer?

10:49.983 --> 10:51.618
‐ Why are we always talking
about "Knots Landing"?

10:51.651 --> 10:53.052
‐ Well, if you watched it,
you would know.

10:53.086 --> 10:55.021
‐ I wish I cared
about anything

10:55.054 --> 10:56.589
as much as they care
about that show.

10:56.623 --> 10:58.258
‐ We care about you...

10:58.291 --> 11:00.059
Almost as much.
‐ [laughs]

11:00.093 --> 11:02.629
‐ My car is out of the shop,
finally.

11:02.662 --> 11:03.596
‐ Finally.
[sighs]

11:03.630 --> 11:04.664
I think that calls
for the cocktail

11:04.697 --> 11:06.733
I was gonna have anyway.

11:06.766 --> 11:08.535
‐ Betty, what about you?
How are you?

11:08.568 --> 11:11.538
‐ I'm good.
I'm good.

11:11.571 --> 11:15.108
I think Dan's banging his
assistant, but, uh, I'm good.

11:15.141 --> 11:18.578
‐ What?
Why would you say that?

11:18.611 --> 11:23.049
‐ Did he?
Has he said that he is?

11:23.082 --> 11:27.453
‐ No.
I don't‐‐

11:27.487 --> 11:30.423
I just‐‐
I think it.

11:30.456 --> 11:33.927
‐ Okay, of course.
There are those men.

11:33.960 --> 11:36.696
We all know them.

11:36.729 --> 11:40.300
But we all know Dan.
Dan isn't like that.

11:40.333 --> 11:43.236
‐ Nobody's like that
until they are.

11:43.269 --> 11:45.572
‐ Okay.
As the only person here

11:45.605 --> 11:47.040
whose husband has
actually cheated on her?

11:47.073 --> 11:49.409
Everyone just step aside.

11:49.442 --> 11:51.377
[clears throat]

11:51.411 --> 11:54.714
Have his habits
suddenly changed?

11:54.747 --> 11:56.282
‐ Yeah, he started
coming home earlier.

11:56.316 --> 11:57.517
‐ [gasps]
That bastard!

11:57.550 --> 11:59.219
‐ [laughs softly]

11:59.252 --> 12:00.787
Does he get
impatient with you

12:00.820 --> 12:04.390
or annoyed at you
for no good reason?

12:04.424 --> 12:06.359
‐ We‐‐we did go through
a patch like that,

12:06.392 --> 12:08.461
but we passed through it.

12:08.494 --> 12:11.197
Things are good now.

12:11.231 --> 12:13.600
‐ Is he still approaching
you sexually?

12:13.633 --> 12:15.268
‐ Karen.
‐ What?

12:15.301 --> 12:16.402
[scoffs]
What?

12:16.436 --> 12:18.104
You're the one that has
something wrong with him.

12:18.137 --> 12:19.772
Everybody loves Dr. Ruth.

12:19.806 --> 12:20.740
[laughter]

12:20.773 --> 12:22.809
‐ Yes.
‐ Ooh.

12:22.842 --> 12:25.712
‐ Of course he is.
Because he loves you.

12:25.745 --> 12:27.380
And because you look
more beautiful

12:27.413 --> 12:28.982
now than you did
when I first met you.

12:29.015 --> 12:30.316
‐ It's true.

12:30.350 --> 12:31.117
‐ Stop it,
you're gonna make me cry.

12:31.150 --> 12:32.151
[whimpers softly]

12:32.185 --> 12:34.988
‐ And also, doesn't the world
already give us

12:35.021 --> 12:36.556
enough real things
to be afraid of?

12:36.589 --> 12:38.558
‐ [groans]
‐ It's true.

12:38.591 --> 12:40.994
Besides,
his work hours are so terrible,

12:41.027 --> 12:42.862
if he did leave me,
I probably wouldn't notice

12:42.895 --> 12:44.664
for about a week.
[laughter]

12:44.697 --> 12:46.799
If my maid left,
on the other hand,

12:46.833 --> 12:48.134
I'd notice that afternoon.

12:48.167 --> 12:51.471
[all laugh]

12:52.205 --> 12:54.807
‐ Case number 352
now on the docket.

12:54.841 --> 12:55.842
‐ There's no way
I'm gonna be able

12:55.875 --> 12:57.010
to write this down fast enough.

12:57.043 --> 12:58.911
I should've
just interviewed Dad at home.

12:58.945 --> 13:00.313
‐ No, this will be a much
better report,

13:00.346 --> 13:01.781
and I have a good memory.
I'll fill in the gaps

13:01.814 --> 13:05.518
if there even are any.
You just do your best.

13:05.551 --> 13:07.453
[door creaks]

13:07.487 --> 13:10.490
[indistinct chatter]

13:10.523 --> 13:13.493
[dramatic music]

13:13.526 --> 13:20.400
♪ ♪

13:32.312 --> 13:33.913
[car honking]

13:36.883 --> 13:38.351
‐ [laughs]

13:38.384 --> 13:41.721
‐ What is this?
Did you buy this?

13:41.754 --> 13:44.290
‐ [inhales]
I tried not to.

13:44.324 --> 13:46.025
‐ [scoffs]
Okay, but isn't it almost like

13:46.059 --> 13:47.627
a spoof on a cliché?
Don't you and Rich Crowley

13:47.660 --> 13:49.796
make fun of the guy who gets
the big settlement

13:49.829 --> 13:52.632
and first thing buys
a red sports car?

13:52.665 --> 13:54.734
‐ Uh, sometimes clichés
are clichés

13:54.767 --> 13:56.269
because they're
goddamn amazing.

13:56.302 --> 13:57.503
[laughs]

13:57.537 --> 13:59.706
Hey, why don't you
find a sitter?

13:59.739 --> 14:03.209
We'll drive up the coast,
have a little overnight, huh?

14:03.242 --> 14:04.777
I mean, this thing handles
like a buttered rocket

14:04.811 --> 14:06.145
on the freeway.

14:06.179 --> 14:08.514
‐ How would you know?
‐ [breathes deeply]

14:08.548 --> 14:10.950
I picked it up in Long Beach,
drove it home.

14:10.983 --> 14:13.619
‐ How'd you get to Long Beach?
‐ [clicks tongue]

14:13.653 --> 14:14.954
[sighs]
I knew you were room mother

14:14.987 --> 14:17.890
for Anthony's class,
so I had Linda take me.

14:21.828 --> 14:24.797
[ambient instrumental music]

14:24.831 --> 14:29.569
♪ ♪

14:29.602 --> 14:32.171
‐ Are we still waiting?
No rush.

14:32.205 --> 14:35.675
‐ I'm actually gonna
go up and check on him.

14:35.708 --> 14:37.810
We're in room 612...

14:37.844 --> 14:41.080
In case we run
out on the check.

14:44.650 --> 14:47.787
[sighs]

14:47.820 --> 14:50.690
[soft dramatic music]

14:50.723 --> 14:52.492
♪ ♪

14:52.525 --> 14:54.494
[elevator dings]

15:01.934 --> 15:05.738
[indistinct chatter]

15:09.375 --> 15:11.611
[chuckles]
Yeah, well...

15:11.644 --> 15:14.280
[inhales]
Hey, hey.

15:14.313 --> 15:15.381
‐ Who are you talking to?

15:15.415 --> 15:17.583
‐ Well, the front desk
told me that the office called.

15:17.617 --> 15:20.453
There's an issue with
